variants.name: Unbonded
docs: A member has unbonded from their pool.
- `balance` is the corresponding balance of the number of points that has been
requested to be unbonded (the argument of the `unbond` transaction) from the bonded
pool.
- `points` is the number of points that are issued as a result of `balance` being
dissolved into the corresponding unbonding pool.
- `era` is the era in which the balance will be unbonded.
In the absence of slashing, these values will match. In the presence of slashing, the
number of points that are issued in the unbonding pool will be less than the amount
requested to be unbonded.

documentation: Hash of the previous block.

documentation: Digest of the current block, also part of the block header.

entries.name: Events
documentation: Events deposited for the current block.
NOTE: The item is unbound and should therefore never be read on chain.
It could otherwise inflate the PoV size of a block.
Events have a large in-memory size. Box the events to not go out-of-memory
just in case someone still reads them from within the runtime.

entries.name: EventCount
documentation: The number of events in the `Events<T>` list.

entries.name: EventTopics
documentation: Mapping between a topic (represented by T::Hash) and a vector of indexes
of events in the `<Events<T>>` list.
All topic vectors have deterministic storage locations depending on the topic. This
allows light-clients to leverage the changes trie storage tracking mechanism and
in case of changes fetch the list of events of interest.
The value has the type `(BlockNumberFor<T>, EventIndex)` because if we used only just
the `EventIndex` then in case if the topic has the same contents on the next block
no notification will be triggered thus the event might be lost.

entries.name: LastRuntimeUpgrade
documentation: Stores the `spec_version` and `spec_name` of when the last runtime upgrade happened.

entries.name: UpgradedToU32RefCount
documentation: True if we have upgraded so that `type RefCount` is `u32`. False (default) if not.

entries.name: UpgradedToTripleRefCount
documentation: True if we have upgraded so that AccountInfo contains three types of `RefCount`. False
(default) if not.

entries.name: ExecutionPhase

constants.name: SS58Prefix

This replaces the "ss58Format" property declared in the chain spec. Reason is
that the runtime should know about the prefix in order to make use of it as
an identifier of the chain.

entries.name: Now
documentation: The current time for the current block.

entries.name: DidUpdate
documentation: Whether the timestamp has been updated in this block.
This value is updated to `true` upon successful submission of a timestamp by a node.
It is then checked at the end of each block execution in the `on_finalize` hook.

constants.name: MinimumPeriod
documentation: The minimum period between blocks.
Be aware that this is different to the *expected* period that the block production
apparatus provides. Your chosen consensus system will generally work with this to
determine a sensible block time. For example, in the Aura pallet it will be double this
period on default settings.

# Security
This MUST NOT be used for gambling, as it can be influenced by a
malicious validator in the short term. It MAY be used in many
cryptographic protocols, however, so long as one remembers that this
(like everything else on-chain) it is public. For example, it can be
used where a number is needed that cannot have been chosen by an
adversary, for purposes such as public-coin zero-knowledge proofs.

entries.name: SegmentIndex
documentation: Randomness under construction.
We make a trade-off between storage accesses and list length.
We store the under-construction randomness in segments of up to
`UNDER_CONSTRUCTION_SEGMENT_LENGTH`.
Once a segment reaches this length, we begin the next one.
We reset all segments and return to `0` at the beginning of every
epoch.

constants.name: OperationalFeeMultiplier
documentation: A fee multiplier for `Operational` extrinsics to compute "virtual tip" to boost their
`priority`
This value is multiplied by the `final_fee` to obtain a "virtual tip" that is later
added to a tip component in regular `priority` calculations.
It means that a `Normal` transaction can front-run a similarly-sized `Operational`
extrinsic (with no tip), by including a tip value greater than the virtual tip.
```rust,ignore
// For `Normal`
let priority = priority_calc(tip);
// For `Operational`
let virtual_tip = (inclusion_fee + tip) * OperationalFeeMultiplier;
let priority = priority_calc(tip + virtual_tip);
Note that since we use `final_fee` the multiplier applies also to the regular `tip`
sent with the transaction. So, not only does the transaction get a priority bump based
on the `inclusion_fee`, but we also amplify the impact of tips applied to `Operational`
transactions.

constants.name: BagThresholds
documentation: The list of thresholds separating the various bags.
Ids are separated into unsorted bags according to their score. This specifies the
thresholds separating the bags. An id's bag is the largest bag for which the id's score
is less than or equal to its upper threshold.
When ids are iterated, higher bags are iterated completely before lower bags. This means
that iteration is _semi-sorted_: ids of higher score tend to come before ids of lower
score, but peer ids within a particular bag are sorted in insertion order.
# Expressing the constant
This constant must be sorted in strictly increasing order. Duplicate items are not
permitted.
There is an implied upper limit of `Score::MAX`; that value does not need to be
specified within the bag. For any two threshold lists, if one ends with
`Score::MAX`, the other one does not, and they are otherwise equal, the two
lists will behave identically.
# Calculation
It is recommended to generate the set of thresholds in a geometric series, such that
there exists some constant ratio such that `threshold[k + 1] == (threshold[k] *
constant_ratio).max(threshold[k] + 1)` for all `k`.
The helpers in the `/utils/frame/generate-bags` module can simplify this calculation.
# Examples
- If `BagThresholds::get().is_empty()`, then all ids are put into the same bag, and
iteration is strictly in insertion order.
- If `BagThresholds::get().len() == 64`, and the thresholds are determined according to
the procedure given above, then the constant ratio is equal to 2.
- If `BagThresholds::get().len() == 200`, and the thresholds are determined according to
the procedure given above, then the constant ratio is approximately equal to 1.248.
- If the threshold list begins `[1, 2, 3, ...]`, then an id with score 0 or 1 will fall
into bag 0, an id with score 2 will fall into bag 1, etc.
# Migration
In the event that this list ever changes, a copy of the old bags list must be retained.
With that `List::migrate` can be called, which will perform the appropriate migration.

entries.name: HeartbeatAfter
documentation: The block number after which it's ok to send heartbeats in the current
session.
At the beginning of each session we set this to a value that should fall
roughly in the middle of the session duration. The idea is to first wait for
the validators to produce a block in the current session, so that the
heartbeat later on will not be necessary.
This value will only be used as a fallback if we fail to get a proper session
progress estimate from `NextSessionRotation`, as those estimates should be
more accurate then the value we calculate for `HeartbeatAfter`.

entries.name: Nominators
documentation: The map from nominator stash key to their nomination preferences, namely the validators that
they wish to support.
Note that the keys of this storage map might become non-decodable in case the
account's [`NominationsQuota::MaxNominations`] configuration is decreased.
In this rare case, these nominators
are still existent in storage, their key is correct and retrievable (i.e. `contains_key`
indicates that they exist), but their value cannot be decoded. Therefore, the non-decodable
nominators will effectively not-exist, until they re-submit their preferences such that it
is within the bounds of the newly set `Config::MaxNominations`.
This implies that `::iter_keys().count()` and `::iter().count()` might return different
values for this map. Moreover, the main `::count()` is aligned with the former, namely the
number of keys that exist.
Lastly, if any of the nominators become non-decodable, they can be chilled immediately via
[`Call::chill_other`] dispatchable by anyone.
TWOX-NOTE: SAFE since `AccountId` is a secure hash.

entries.name: CurrentEra
documentation: The current era index.
This is the latest planned era, depending on how the Session pallet queues the validator

entries.name: ActiveEra
documentation: The active era information, it holds index and start.
The active era is the era being currently rewarded. Validator set of this era must be

entries.name: ErasStartSessionIndex
documentation: The session index at which the era start for the last [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.
Note: This tracks the starting session (i.e. session index when era start being active)
for the eras in `[CurrentEra - HISTORY_DEPTH, CurrentEra]`.

entries.name: ErasStakers
documentation: Exposure of validator at era.
This is keyed first by the era index to allow bulk deletion and then the stash account.
Is it removed after [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.
If stakers hasn't been set or has been removed then empty exposure is returned.
Note: Deprecated since v14. Use `EraInfo` instead to work with exposures.

entries.name: ErasStakersOverview
documentation: Summary of validator exposure at a given era.
This contains the total stake in support of the validator and their own stake. In addition,
it can also be used to get the number of nominators backing this validator and the number of
exposure pages they are divided into. The page count is useful to determine the number of
pages of rewards that needs to be claimed.
This is keyed first by the era index to allow bulk deletion and then the stash account.
Should only be accessed through `EraInfo`.
Is it removed after [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.
If stakers hasn't been set or has been removed then empty overview is returned.

entries.name: ErasStakersClipped
documentation: Clipped Exposure of validator at era.
Note: This is deprecated, should be used as read-only and will be removed in the future.
New `Exposure`s are stored in a paged manner in `ErasStakersPaged` instead.
This is similar to [`ErasStakers`] but number of nominators exposed is reduced to the
`T::MaxExposurePageSize` biggest stakers.
(Note: the field `total` and `own` of the exposure remains unchanged).
This is used to limit the i/o cost for the nominator payout.
This is keyed fist by the era index to allow bulk deletion and then the stash account.
It is removed after [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.
If stakers hasn't been set or has been removed then empty exposure is returned.
Note: Deprecated since v14. Use `EraInfo` instead to work with exposures.

entries.name: ErasStakersPaged
documentation: Paginated exposure of a validator at given era.
This is keyed first by the era index to allow bulk deletion, then stash account and finally
the page. Should only be accessed through `EraInfo`.
This is cleared after [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.

entries.name: ClaimedRewards
documentation: History of claimed paged rewards by era and validator.
This is keyed by era and validator stash which maps to the set of page indexes which have
been claimed.
It is removed after [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.

entries.name: ErasValidatorPrefs
documentation: Similar to `ErasStakers`, this holds the preferences of validators.
This is keyed first by the era index to allow bulk deletion and then the stash account.
Is it removed after [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.

entries.name: ErasValidatorReward

Eras that haven't finished yet or has been removed doesn't have reward.

entries.name: ErasRewardPoints

If reward hasn't been set or has been removed then 0 reward is returned.

entries.name: ErasTotalStake
documentation: The total amount staked for the last [`Config::HistoryDepth`] eras.
If total hasn't been set or has been removed then 0 stake is returned.

The rest of the slashed value is handled by the `Slash`.

entries.name: CanceledSlashPayout
documentation: The amount of currency given to reporters of a slash event which was
canceled by extraordinary circumstances (e.g. governance).

entries.name: UnappliedSlashes
documentation: All unapplied slashes that are queued for later.

entries.name: BondedEras
documentation: A mapping from still-bonded eras to the first session index of that era.
Must contains information for eras for the range:
`[active_era - bounding_duration; active_era]`

entries.name: ValidatorSlashInEra
documentation: All slashing events on validators, mapped by era to the highest slash proportion
and slash value of the era.

entries.name: NominatorSlashInEra

entries.name: SlashingSpans

entries.name: SpanSlash

as well as how much reward has been paid out.

entries.name: CurrentPlannedSession
documentation: The last planned session scheduled by the session pallet.
This is basically in sync with the call to [`pallet_session::SessionManager::new_session`].

entries.name: OffendingValidators
documentation: Indices of validators that have offended in the active era and whether they are currently
disabled.
This value should be a superset of disabled validators since not all offences lead to the
validator being disabled (if there was no slash). This is needed to track the percentage of
validators that have offended in the current era, ensuring a new era is forced if
`OffendingValidatorsThreshold` is reached. The vec is always kept sorted so that we can find
whether a given validator has previously offended using binary search. It gets cleared when
the era ends.

entries.name: ChillThreshold
documentation: The threshold for when users can start calling `chill_other` for other validators /
nominators. The threshold is compared to the actual number of validators / nominators
(`CountFor*`) in the system compared to the configured max (`Max*Count`).

constants.name: HistoryDepth
documentation: Number of eras to keep in history.
Following information is kept for eras in `[current_era -
HistoryDepth, current_era]`: `ErasStakers`, `ErasStakersClipped`,
`ErasValidatorPrefs`, `ErasValidatorReward`, `ErasRewardPoints`,
`ErasTotalStake`, `ErasStartSessionIndex`, `ClaimedRewards`, `ErasStakersPaged`,
`ErasStakersOverview`.
Must be more than the number of eras delayed by session.
I.e. active era must always be in history. I.e. `active_era >
current_era - history_depth` must be guaranteed.
If migrating an existing pallet from storage value to config value,
this should be set to same value or greater as in storage.
Note: `HistoryDepth` is used as the upper bound for the `BoundedVec`
item `StakingLedger.legacy_claimed_rewards`. Setting this value lower than
the existing value can lead to inconsistencies in the
`StakingLedger` and will need to be handled properly in a migration.
The test `reducing_history_depth_abrupt` shows this effect.

constants.name: SessionsPerEra
documentation: Number of sessions per era.

constants.name: BondingDuration
documentation: Number of eras that staked funds must remain bonded for.

constants.name: SlashDeferDuration
documentation: Number of eras that slashes are deferred by, after computation.
This should be less than the bonding duration. Set to 0 if slashes
should be applied immediately, without opportunity for intervention.

constants.name: MaxExposurePageSize
documentation: The maximum size of each `T::ExposurePage`.
An `ExposurePage` is weakly bounded to a maximum of `MaxExposurePageSize`
nominators.
For older non-paged exposure, a reward payout was restricted to the top
`MaxExposurePageSize` nominators. This is to limit the i/o cost for the
nominator payout.
Note: `MaxExposurePageSize` is used to bound `ClaimedRewards` and is unsafe to reduce
without handling it in a migration.

constants.name: MaxUnlockingChunks
documentation: The maximum number of `unlocking` chunks a [`StakingLedger`] can
have. Effectively determines how many unique eras a staker may be
unbonding in.
Note: `MaxUnlockingChunks` is used as the upper bound for the
`BoundedVec` item `StakingLedger.unlocking`. Setting this value
lower than the existing value can lead to inconsistencies in the
`StakingLedger` and will need to be handled properly in a runtime
migration. The test `reducing_max_unlocking_chunks_abrupt` shows
this effect.

constants.name: AlarmInterval
documentation: Quantization level for the referendum wakeup scheduler. A higher number will result in
fewer storage reads/writes needed for smaller voters, but also result in delays to the
automatic referendum status changes. Explicit servicing instructions are unaffected.

constants.name: Tracks
documentation: Information concerning the different referendum tracks.

entries.name: Agenda
documentation: Items to be executed, indexed by the block number that they should be executed on.

entries.name: Lookup
documentation: Lookup from a name to the block number and index of the task.
For v3 -> v4 the previously unbounded identities are Blake2-256 hashed to form the v4
identities.

constants.name: MaximumWeight
documentation: The maximum weight that may be scheduled per block for any dispatchables.

constants.name: MaxScheduledPerBlock
documentation: The maximum number of scheduled calls in the queue for a single block.
NOTE:
+ Dependent pallets' benchmarks might require a higher limit for the setting. Set a
higher limit under `runtime-benchmarks` feature.

entries.name: StatusFor
documentation: The request status of a given hash.

entries.name: RequestStatusFor
documentation: The request status of a given hash.

entries.name: IdentityOf
documentation: Information that is pertinent to identify the entity behind an account.
TWOX-NOTE: OK ― `AccountId` is a secure hash.

entries.name: SuperOf
documentation: The super-identity of an alternative "sub" identity together with its name, within that
context. If the account is not some other account's sub-identity, then just `None`.

entries.name: SubsOf
documentation: Alternative "sub" identities of this account.
The first item is the deposit, the second is a vector of the accounts.
TWOX-NOTE: OK ― `AccountId` is a secure hash.

entries.name: Registrars
documentation: The set of registrars. Not expected to get very big as can only be added through a
special origin (likely a council motion).
The index into this can be cast to `RegistrarIndex` to get a valid value.

constants.name: BasicDeposit
documentation: The amount held on deposit for a registered identity

constants.name: ByteDeposit
documentation: The amount held on deposit per encoded byte for a registered identity.

constants.name: SubAccountDeposit
documentation: The amount held on deposit for a registered subaccount. This should account for the fact
that one storage item's value will increase by the size of an account ID, and there will
be another trie item whose value is the size of an account ID plus 32 bytes.

constants.name: MaxSubAccounts
documentation: The maximum number of sub-accounts allowed per identified account.

constants.name: MaxRegistrars
documentation: Maxmimum number of registrars allowed in the system. Needed to bound the complexity
of, e.g., updating judgements.

entries.name: Proxies
documentation: The set of account proxies. Maps the account which has delegated to the accounts
which are being delegated to, together with the amount held on deposit.

entries.name: Announcements
documentation: The announcements made by the proxy (key).

constants.name: ProxyDepositBase
documentation: The base amount of currency needed to reserve for creating a proxy.
This is held for an additional storage item whose value size is
`sizeof(Balance)` bytes and whose key size is `sizeof(AccountId)` bytes.

constants.name: ProxyDepositFactor
documentation: The amount of currency needed per proxy added.
This is held for adding 32 bytes plus an instance of `ProxyType` more into a
pre-existing storage value. Thus, when configuring `ProxyDepositFactor` one should take
into account `32 + proxy_type.encode().len()` bytes of data.

constants.name: MaxProxies
documentation: The maximum amount of proxies allowed for a single account.

constants.name: MaxPending
documentation: The maximum amount of time-delayed announcements that are allowed to be pending.

constants.name: AnnouncementDepositBase
documentation: The base amount of currency needed to reserve for creating an announcement.
This is held when a new storage item holding a `Balance` is created (typically 16
bytes).

constants.name: AnnouncementDepositFactor
documentation: The amount of currency needed per announcement made.
This is held for adding an `AccountId`, `Hash` and `BlockNumber` (typically 68 bytes)
into a pre-existing storage value.

entries.name: Multisigs
documentation: The set of open multisig operations.

constants.name: DepositBase
documentation: The base amount of currency needed to reserve for creating a multisig execution or to
store a dispatch call for later.
This is held for an additional storage item whose value size is
`4 + sizeof((BlockNumber, Balance, AccountId))` bytes and whose key size is
`32 + sizeof(AccountId)` bytes.

constants.name: DepositFactor
documentation: The amount of currency needed per unit threshold when creating a multisig execution.
This is held for adding 32 bytes more into a pre-existing storage value.

constants.name: MaxSignatories
documentation: The maximum amount of signatories allowed in the multisig.

entries.name: Round
documentation: Internal counter for the number of rounds.
This is useful for de-duplication of transactions submitted to the pool, and general
diagnostics of the pallet.
This is merely incremented once per every time that an upstream `elect` is called.

entries.name: CurrentPhase
documentation: Current phase.

entries.name: QueuedSolution
documentation: Current best solution, signed or unsigned, queued to be returned upon `elect`.
Always sorted by score.

entries.name: Snapshot
documentation: Snapshot data of the round.
This is created at the beginning of the signed phase and cleared upon calling `elect`.

entries.name: DesiredTargets
documentation: Desired number of targets to elect for this round.
Only exists when [`Snapshot`] is present.

entries.name: SnapshotMetadata
documentation: The metadata of the [`RoundSnapshot`]
Only exists when [`Snapshot`] is present.

entries.name: SignedSubmissionNextIndex
documentation: The next index to be assigned to an incoming signed submission.
Every accepted submission is assigned a unique index; that index is bound to that particular
submission for the duration of the election. On election finalization, the next index is
reset to 0.
We can't just use `SignedSubmissionIndices.len()`, because that's a bounded set; past its
capacity, it will simply saturate. We can't just iterate over `SignedSubmissionsMap`,
because iteration is slow. Instead, we store the value here.

entries.name: SignedSubmissionIndices
documentation: A sorted, bounded vector of `(score, block_number, index)`, where each `index` points to a
value in `SignedSubmissions`.
We never need to process more than a single signed submission at a time. Signed submissions
can be quite large, so we're willing to pay the cost of multiple database accesses to access
them one at a time instead of reading and decoding all of them at once.

entries.name: SignedSubmissionsMap
documentation: Unchecked, signed solutions.
Together with `SubmissionIndices`, this stores a bounded set of `SignedSubmissions` while
allowing us to keep only a single one in memory at a time.
Twox note: the key of the map is an auto-incrementing index which users cannot inspect or
affect; we shouldn't need a cryptographically secure hasher.

entries.name: MinimumUntrustedScore
documentation: The minimum score that each 'untrusted' solution must attain in order to be considered
feasible.
Can be set via `set_minimum_untrusted_score`.

constants.name: UnsignedPhase
documentation: Duration of the unsigned phase.

constants.name: SignedPhase
documentation: Duration of the signed phase.

constants.name: BetterSignedThreshold
documentation: The minimum amount of improvement to the solution score that defines a solution as
"better" in the Signed phase.

constants.name: BetterUnsignedThreshold
documentation: The minimum amount of improvement to the solution score that defines a solution as
"better" in the Unsigned phase.

constants.name: OffchainRepeat
documentation: The repeat threshold of the offchain worker.
For example, if it is 5, that means that at least 5 blocks will elapse between attempts
to submit the worker's solution.

constants.name: MinerTxPriority
documentation: The priority of the unsigned transaction submitted in the unsigned-phase

constants.name: SignedMaxSubmissions
documentation: Maximum number of signed submissions that can be queued.
It is best to avoid adjusting this during an election, as it impacts downstream data
structures. In particular, `SignedSubmissionIndices<T>` is bounded on this value. If you
update this value during an election, you _must_ ensure that
`SignedSubmissionIndices.len()` is less than or equal to the new value. Otherwise,
attempts to submit new solutions may cause a runtime panic.

constants.name: SignedMaxWeight
documentation: Maximum weight of a signed solution.
If [`Config::MinerConfig`] is being implemented to submit signed solutions (outside of
this pallet), then [`MinerConfig::solution_weight`] is used to compare against
this value.

constants.name: SignedMaxRefunds
documentation: The maximum amount of unchecked solutions to refund the call fee for.

constants.name: SignedRewardBase
documentation: Base reward for a signed solution

constants.name: SignedDepositByte
documentation: Per-byte deposit for a signed solution.

constants.name: SignedDepositWeight
documentation: Per-weight deposit for a signed solution.

constants.name: MaxWinners
documentation: The maximum number of winners that can be elected by this `ElectionProvider`
implementation.
Note: This must always be greater or equal to `T::DataProvider::desired_targets()`.

entries.name: Reports
documentation: The primary structure that holds all offence records keyed by report identifiers.

entries.name: ConcurrentReportsIndex
documentation: A vector of reports of the same kind that happened at the same time slot.

entries.name: BountyCount
documentation: Number of bounty proposals that have been made.

entries.name: Bounties
documentation: Bounties that have been made.

entries.name: BountyDescriptions
documentation: The description of each bounty.

entries.name: BountyApprovals
documentation: Bounty indices that have been approved but not yet funded.

constants.name: BountyDepositBase
documentation: The amount held on deposit for placing a bounty proposal.

constants.name: BountyDepositPayoutDelay
documentation: The delay period for which a bounty beneficiary need to wait before claim the payout.

constants.name: BountyUpdatePeriod
documentation: Bounty duration in blocks.

constants.name: CuratorDepositMultiplier
documentation: The curator deposit is calculated as a percentage of the curator fee.
This deposit has optional upper and lower bounds with `CuratorDepositMax` and
`CuratorDepositMin`.

constants.name: CuratorDepositMax
documentation: Maximum amount of funds that should be placed in a deposit for making a proposal.

constants.name: CuratorDepositMin
documentation: Minimum amount of funds that should be placed in a deposit for making a proposal.

constants.name: BountyValueMinimum
documentation: Minimum value for a bounty.

constants.name: DataDepositPerByte
documentation: The amount held on deposit per byte within the tip report reason or bounty description.

constants.name: MaximumReasonLength
documentation: Maximum acceptable reason length.
Benchmarks depend on this value, be sure to update weights file when changing this value

entries.name: ChildBountyCount
documentation: Number of total child bounties.

entries.name: ParentChildBounties
documentation: Number of child bounties per parent bounty.
Map of parent bounty index to number of child bounties.

entries.name: ChildBounties
documentation: Child bounties that have been added.

entries.name: ChildBountyDescriptions
documentation: The description of each child-bounty.

entries.name: ChildrenCuratorFees
documentation: The cumulative child-bounty curator fee for each parent bounty.

constants.name: MaxActiveChildBountyCount
documentation: Maximum number of child bounties that can be added to a parent bounty.

constants.name: ChildBountyValueMinimum
documentation: Minimum value for a child-bounty.

entries.name: TotalValueLocked
documentation: The sum of funds across all pools.
This might be lower but never higher than the sum of `total_balance` of all [`PoolMembers`]
because calling `pool_withdraw_unbonded` might decrease the total stake of the pool's
`bonded_account` without adjusting the pallet-internal `UnbondingPool`'s.

entries.name: MinJoinBond
documentation: Minimum amount to bond to join a pool.

entries.name: MinCreateBond
documentation: Minimum bond required to create a pool.
This is the amount that the depositor must put as their initial stake in the pool, as an
indication of "skin in the game".
This is the value that will always exist in the staking ledger of the pool bonded account
while all other accounts leave.

entries.name: MaxPools
documentation: Maximum number of nomination pools that can exist. If `None`, then an unbounded number of
pools can exist.

entries.name: MaxPoolMembers
documentation: Maximum number of members that can exist in the system. If `None`, then the count
members are not bound on a system wide basis.

entries.name: MaxPoolMembersPerPool
documentation: Maximum number of members that may belong to pool. If `None`, then the count of
members is not bound on a per pool basis.

entries.name: GlobalMaxCommission
documentation: The maximum commission that can be charged by a pool. Used on commission payouts to bound
pool commissions that are > `GlobalMaxCommission`, necessary if a future
`GlobalMaxCommission` is lower than some current pool commissions.

entries.name: PoolMembers
documentation: Active members.
TWOX-NOTE: SAFE since `AccountId` is a secure hash.

entries.name: CounterForPoolMembers
documentation: Counter for the related counted storage map

entries.name: BondedPools
documentation: Storage for bonded pools.

entries.name: CounterForBondedPools
documentation: Counter for the related counted storage map

entries.name: RewardPools
documentation: Reward pools. This is where there rewards for each pool accumulate. When a members payout is
claimed, the balance comes out fo the reward pool. Keyed by the bonded pools account.

entries.name: CounterForRewardPools
documentation: Counter for the related counted storage map

entries.name: SubPoolsStorage
documentation: Groups of unbonding pools. Each group of unbonding pools belongs to a
bonded pool, hence the name sub-pools. Keyed by the bonded pools account.

entries.name: CounterForSubPoolsStorage
documentation: Counter for the related counted storage map

entries.name: Metadata
documentation: Metadata for the pool.

entries.name: CounterForMetadata
documentation: Counter for the related counted storage map

entries.name: LastPoolId
documentation: Ever increasing number of all pools created so far.

entries.name: ReversePoolIdLookup
documentation: A reverse lookup from the pool's account id to its id.
This is only used for slashing. In all other instances, the pool id is used, and the
accounts are deterministically derived from it.

entries.name: CounterForReversePoolIdLookup
documentation: Counter for the related counted storage map

entries.name: ClaimPermissions
documentation: Map from a pool member account to their opted claim permission.

constants.name: PalletId
documentation: The nomination pool's pallet id.

constants.name: MaxPointsToBalance
documentation: The maximum pool points-to-balance ratio that an `open` pool can have.
This is important in the event slashing takes place and the pool's points-to-balance
ratio becomes disproportional.
Moreover, this relates to the `RewardCounter` type as well, as the arithmetic operations
are a function of number of points, and by setting this value to e.g. 10, you ensure
that the total number of points in the system are at most 10 times the total_issuance of
the chain, in the absolute worse case.
For a value of 10, the threshold would be a pool points-to-balance ratio of 10:1.
Such a scenario would also be the equivalent of the pool being 90% slashed.

entries.name: CounterForDispatches
documentation: Counter for the related counted storage map

constants.name: ReserveThreshold
documentation: Amount of blocks for extra delay used to secure from outdated tasks.

constants.name: WaitlistCost
documentation: Cost for storing in waitlist per block.

constants.name: MailboxCost
documentation: Cost for storing in mailbox per block.

constants.name: ReservationCost
documentation: Cost for reservation holding.

constants.name: DispatchHoldCost
documentation: Cost for reservation holding.

constants.name: BlockGasLimit
documentation: The maximum amount of gas that can be used within a single block.

entries.name: ExecuteInherent
documentation: A flag indicating whether the message queue should be processed at the end of a block
If not set, the inherent extrinsic that processes the queue will keep throwing an error
thereby making the block builder exclude it from the block.

entries.name: BlockNumber
documentation: The current block number being processed.
It shows block number in which queue is processed.
May be less than system pallet block number if panic occurred previously.

entries.name: GearRunInBlock
documentation: A guard to prohibit all but the first execution of `pallet_gear::run()` call in a block.
Set to `Some(())` if the extrinsic is executed for the first time in a block.
All subsequent attempts would fail with `Error::<T>::GearRunAlreadyInBlock` error.
Set back to `None` in the `on_finalize()` hook at the end of the block.

constants.name: Schedule
documentation: Cost schedule and limits.

constants.name: OutgoingLimit
documentation: The maximum amount of messages that can be produced in during all message executions.

constants.name: OutgoingBytesLimit
documentation: The maximum amount of bytes in outgoing messages during message execution.

constants.name: PerformanceMultiplier
documentation: Performance multiplier.

constants.name: MailboxThreshold
documentation: The minimal gas amount for message to be inserted in mailbox.
This gas will be consuming as rent for storing and message will be available
for reply or claim, once gas ends, message removes.
Messages with gas limit less than that minimum will not be added in mailbox,
but will be seen in events.

constants.name: ReservationsLimit
documentation: Amount of reservations can exist for 1 program.

constants.name: ProgramRentFreePeriod
documentation: The free of charge period of rent.

constants.name: ProgramResumeMinimalRentPeriod
documentation: The minimal amount of blocks to resume.

constants.name: ProgramRentCostPerBlock
documentation: The program rent cost per block.

constants.name: ProgramResumeSessionDuration
documentation: The amount of blocks for processing resume session.

constants.name: ProgramRentEnabled
documentation: The flag determines if program rent mechanism enabled.

constants.name: ProgramRentDisabledDelta
documentation: The constant defines value that is added if the program
rent is disabled.

constants.name: RentPoolId
documentation: The account id of the rent pool if any.

entries.name: TargetInflation
documentation: Target inflation (at ideal stake)

entries.name: IdealStakingRatio
documentation: Ideal staking ratio

entries.name: NonStakeableShare
documentation: The current share of issued tokens that cannot be staked (e.g. being vested)
This value is guaranteed to remain unchanged for the first year until vesting kicks in.
Subsequently, the non-stakeable share should be calculated based on the vesting balances.

entries.name: FilteredAccounts
documentation: List of accounts whose locked balance (due to incomplete vesting) should be excluded from
the total stakeable quantity.
During the 1st year the non-stakeable amount is accounted for as a fixed fraction of TTS.

constants.name: PalletId
documentation: The staking rewards' pallet id, used for deriving its sovereign account ID.

constants.name: MillisecondsPerYear
documentation: Milliseconds per year to calculate inflation.

constants.name: MinInflation
documentation: Minimum annual inflation.

constants.name: MaxROI
documentation: ROI cap.

constants.name: Falloff
documentation: Exponential decay (fall-off) parameter.

entries.name: Issued
documentation: Storage containing amount of the total vouchers issued.
Used as nonce in voucher creation.

entries.name: Vouchers
documentation: Double map storage containing data of the voucher,
associated with some spender and voucher ids.

constants.name: PalletId
documentation: The pallet id, used for deriving its sovereign account ID.

constants.name: MaxProgramsAmount
documentation: Maximal amount of programs to be specified to interact with.

constants.name: MinDuration
documentation: Minimal duration in blocks voucher could be issued/prolonged for.

constants.name: MaxDuration
documentation: Maximal duration in blocks voucher could be issued/prolonged for.

constants.name: BankAddress
documentation: Bank account address, that will keep all reserved funds.

constants.name: GasMultiplier
documentation: Gas price converter.

entries.name: Initialized
documentation: Lifecycle storage.
Defines if pallet got initialized and focused on common session changes.

entries.name: Paused
documentation: Lifecycle storage.
Defines if pallet is accepting any mutable requests. Governance-ruled.

entries.name: AuthoritySetHash
documentation: Primary storage.
Keeps hash of queued validator keys for the next era.
**Invariant**: Key exists in storage since first block of some era's last
session, until initialization of the second block of the next era.

entries.name: QueueMerkleRoot
documentation: Primary storage.
Keeps merkle root of the bridge's queued messages.
**Invariant**: Key exists since pallet initialization. If queue is empty,
zeroed hash set in storage.

entries.name: Queue
documentation: Primary storage.
Keeps bridge's queued messages keccak hashes.

entries.name: SessionsTimer
documentation: Operational storage.
Declares timer of the session changes (`on_new_session` calls),
when `queued_validators` must be stored within the pallet.
**Invariant**: reducing each time on new session, it equals 0 only
since storing grandpa keys hash until next session change,
when it becomes `SessionPerEra - 1`.

entries.name: ClearTimer
documentation: Operational storage.
Defines in how many on_initialize hooks queue, queue merkle root and
grandpa keys hash should be cleared.
**Invariant**: set to 2 on_init hooks when new session with authorities
set change, then decreasing to zero on each new block hook. When equals
to zero, reset is performed.

entries.name: MessageNonce
documentation: Operational storage.
Keeps next message's nonce for bridging. Must be increased on each use.

entries.name: QueueChanged
documentation: Operational storage.
Defines if queue was changed within the block, it's necessary to
update queue merkle root by the end of the block.

constants.name: MaxPayloadSize
documentation: Constant defining maximal payload size in bytes of message for bridging.

constants.name: QueueCapacity
documentation: Constant defining maximal amount of messages that are able to be
bridged within the single staking era.

constants.name: SessionsPerEra
documentation: Constant defining amount of sessions in manager for keys rotation.
Similar to `pallet_staking::SessionsPerEra`.

entries.name: Key
documentation: The `AccountId` of the sudo key.
